<HEADLINE>
<P>
INVESTING IN DAVE KOZ 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In regard to Don Heckman's review, "Dave Koz Takes the Easy Commercial Path at 
Strand" (Feb. 22): I attended Koz's performance and walked away thoroughly 
impressed by an instrumental performer who had enough regard for his audience 
to entertain them with his charmingly infectious personality, as well as what I 
(according to Heckman) wrongly perceived as an abundance of musicianship. 
</P>
<P>
 My problem with most instrumental performers is that they seem to be so 
cerebrally intent on playing every note ever created that I find myself lost 
and thinking about anything but the music.This was not the case with Koz. His 
songs were memorable and the solos succinct. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite the headline, I'm sure that there is a myriad of sax players 
struggling desperately to get on that commercial path. I, for one, felt that 
the show was a thoroughly enjoyable investment of my time and money. 
</P>
<P>
 GAIL BIRNS 
</P>
<P>
 Culver City 
</P>
