<HEADLINE>
<P>
DOLLARS AND THE ORCHESTRA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I read with great interest the article detailing the financial troubles being 
experienced by the Los Angeles Chamber Orchestra ("Tough Road Ahead for L.A. 
Chamber Orchestra," Feb. 15). 
</P>
<P>
 The article did not mention that the orchestra sometimes works in the pit for 
the Los Angeles Opera.Don't they get some compensation for that? 
</P>
<P>
 And here is a golden opportunity for our two major classical radio stations 
(KUSC-FM and KKGO-FM) to help save this orchestra by doing fund-raising. Both 
could spur listener interest in sending tax-deductible contributions ($5, $10, 
$15) to the orchestra. Maybe they could bring the conductor or members of the 
board to the stations to ask for support. To a lesser extent, KCSN-FM, KPFK-FM, 
KCRW-FM or others that program classical music on a part-time basis might also 
help. 
</P>
<P>
 And, if corporate people could see that there is community support, they might 
help as well. 
</P>
<P>
 GORDON A. SOLOMON 
