<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROBBINS LOSES REAL ESTATE LICENSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CYNTHIA H. CRAFT, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Despite his emotional plea that "I've paid my price," former state Sen. Alan 
Robbins was stripped of his real estate license Friday, five weeks after he 
told an administrative law judge that he had been punished enough as a 
convicted felon. 
</P>
<P>
 Robbins, who is scheduled to be released from a Hollywood halfway house next 
week after serving less than two years of his original five-year sentence, 
pleaded guilty in 1992 to political-corruption charges for using his Van Nuys 
Senate seat to extort money from people seeking legislative favors. 
</P>
<P>
 He is awaiting sentencing on a federal bank fraud conviction for failing to 
disclose information in seeking a $900,000 loan from Independence Bank of 
Encino. 
</P>
<P>
 State Real Estate Commissioner Clark Wallace ruled Friday that Robbins' 
license should be revoked because his crimes went to the heart of the issues of 
truthfulness, honesty and moral turpitude, said Dan Garrett, spokesman for the 
state Department of Real Estate. 
</P>
<P>
 "There was clear and convincing evidence that Mr. Robbins' crimes were 
relevant to the qualifications of licensure," Garrett said. 
</P>
<P>
 But Robbins, saying he will consider an appeal, reiterated Friday that he 
feels he paid his debt to society and deserves a second chance. 
</P>
<P>
 "It doesn't seem fair that, after I've paid my price for the things I did that 
were illegal, that I would be punished further by the state Department of Real 
Estate," Robbins said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
 The 50-year-old former lawmaker said he has already been denied the use of his 
broker's license during the nearly two years he spent in a federal prison in 
Lompoc and the halfway house. 
</P>
<P>
 With no future in politics, no license to practice law and, now, no broker's 
license, Robbins -- who amassed his wealth through real estate deals -- said he 
is uncertain how he will make a living. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's something I'll have to work out," Robbins said. "I suspect there are 
several options that I can go over with my attorney, but I'm not sure what they 
are at the moment." 
</P>
<P>
 In making his case to an administrative law judge Jan. 28, Robbins presented 
numerous letters of support from such political figures as former state Sen. Ed 
Davis and former Assemblyman Tom Bane. 
</P>
<P>
 Other letters testifying to Robbins' character came from UCLA Chancellor 
Charles Young; Charles Fuentes, a former aide to City Atty. James K. Hahn; and 
James Montgomery, a leader in the San Fernando Valley chapter of the NAACP. 
</P>
<P>
 But Administrative Law Judge Richard J. Lopez nevertheless recommended that 
Robbins be denied his license, Garrett said. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was trying to convince the judge he was essentially reformed, with 
character witnesses and all," Garrett said. "But it didn't work. It was a 
pretty straightforward case." 
</P>
<P>
 Robbins, who championed San Fernando Valley issues in the Legislature for 
nearly two decades, can ask for a 30-day stay of Wallace's decision while he 
files an appeal, Garrett said. 
</P>
<P>
 Failing the appeal, Robbins can wait two years and reapply for his license, 
which enables brokers to take part in a range of industrial, commercial and 
residential transactions, Garrett said. 
</P>
<P>
 Between 500 and 600 brokers lose their licenses in California annually, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Robbins said he regrets Wallace's decision partly because he had planned to 
apply real estate commissions to the approximately $4 million he still owes the 
federal government. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would certainly hope that this action would not be used to keep the 
government out of their money," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
