<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEACHER HONORED IN EMOTIONAL CEREMONY; EDUCATION: PACOIMA MIDDLE SCHOOL'S RUTH 
BROWN, FORCED TO RETIRE BECAUSE OF ILLNESS, IS PRAISED BY MAYOR. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By By HUGO MARTIN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If Ruth Brown had her way, she would teach at Pacoima Middle School for 
another 34 years. But time and her deteriorating health won't allow it. 
</P>
<P>
 Brown, who began as a physical fitness teacher in 1960 and later moved up to 
dean of students, was forced to leave her job in January due to a malignant 
brain tumor that made it increasingly difficult for her to perform her duties. 
</P>
<P>
 But her 34 years as an educator and youth volunteer in the predominantly 
Latino, working-class neighborhood have not gone unrecognized. 
</P>
<P>
 Accompanied by her daughter and her former principal, Brown was awarded a 
certificate of recognition Friday from the Los Angeles Unified School District 
and the City Council in an emotional ceremony at City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would not have retired as long as I was effective," said Brown, choking 
back tears. "But we are all given a deck of cards and we play them out." 
</P>
<P>
 In a brief gathering after the presentation, Brown was praised by district 
administrators and city officials, including Mayor Richard Riordan, who called 
Brown "the greatest teacher in the history of the world." 
</P>
<P>
 "How does it feel to be the greatest teacher in the world?" the mayor asked 
her. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't know," she answered seriously. "I think it would feel better if I 
were still teaching." 
</P>
<P>
 Maria Wale, principal of Pacoima Middle School, said Brown was the first 
person to welcome her when she arrived several years ago to become the school's 
first female principal. 
</P>
<P>
 Since then, Wale said Brown has "always been in the forefront in trying to 
make sure everybody else was comfortable and happy." 
</P>
<P>
 The students liked Brown so much that a few years ago they dedicated the 
yearbook to her. And faculty members respected her so much that they elected 
her dean of students in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
 "I will tell you that Ruth Brown has been the guardian angel of Pacoima Middle 
School," Wale said. "I believe in angels." 
</P>
</TEXT>
